item.title: Jessica add a quote by Lucy Maud Montgomery
item.description: "It's not vanity to know your own good points. It would just be stupidity if you didn't; It's only vanity when you get puffed up about them." -- Lucy Maud Montgomery

item.title: Jessica add a quote by Jane Austen
item.description: "I do not want people to be very agreeable, as it saves me the trouble of liking them a great deal." -- Jane Austen

item.title: Jessica add a quote by Jane Austen
item.description: "The person, be it gentleman or lady, who has not pleasure in a good novel, must be intolerably stupid." -- Jane Austen

item.title: Jessica add a quote by Jane Austen
item.description: "A lady's imagination is very rapid; it jumps from admiration to love, from love to matrimony in a moment." -- Jane Austen

item.title: Jessica add a quote by Jane Austen
item.description: "I declare after all there is no enjoyment like reading! How much sooner one tires of any thing than of a book! -- When I have a house of my own, I shall be miserable if I have not an excellent library." -- Jane Austen

item.title: Jessica add a quote by Jane Austen
item.description: "For what do we live, but to make sport for our neighbors, and laugh at them in our turn?" -- Jane Austen

item.title: Jessica add a quote by Jane Austen
item.description: "I always deserve the best treatment because I never put up with any other." -- Jane Austen

item.title: Jessica add a quote by Charlotte Bronte
Jessica add a quote by Charlotte Brontë
item.description: "The soul, fortunately, has an interpreter - often an unconscious but still a faithful interpreter - in the eye." -- Charlotte Brontë

item.title: Jessica add a quote by Ian McEwan
item.description: "A person is, among all else, a material thing, easily torn and not easily mended." -- Ian McEwan

item.title: Jessica add a quote by Ian McEwan
item.description: "A story was a form of telepathy. By means of inking symbols onto a page, she was able to send thoughts and feelings from her mind to her reader's. It was a magical process, so commonplace that no one stopped to wonder at it." -- Ian McEwan
